👥 Stakeholder Mapping
Automated Employee Onboarding & Offboarding System

Stakeholder mapping identifies who is involved in the system, what they need, what they control, and how they interact with the onboarding/offboarding lifecycle.

1. Overview

The system involves multiple stakeholders across:

HR operations
IT infrastructure
Security & compliance
Management
Employees
External systems

Each stakeholder has different goals, permissions, and responsibilities.

2. Stakeholder Categories
2.1 Primary Stakeholders (Direct Users)
👤 HR Team

Role: Owns employee lifecycle initiation

Responsibilities:

Create employee records
Trigger onboarding workflows
Manage exit requests
Ensure documentation compliance

System Interaction:

Employee module
Onboarding dashboard
Offboarding approvals
🖥️ IT Team

Role: Manages system access and infrastructure

Responsibilities:

Create user accounts
Provision/deprovision system access
Manage IAM integrations
Handle technical onboarding

System Interaction:

Access Control module
IAM integration layer
Workflow engine
👨‍💼 Managers

Role: Approve and supervise employee lifecycle

Responsibilities:

Approve onboarding
Assign onboarding tasks
Approve offboarding
Monitor team access

System Interaction:

Approval dashboards
Task management interface
👩‍💻 Employees

Role: End users undergoing onboarding/offboarding

Responsibilities:

Complete onboarding checklist
Submit required documents
Complete training
Acknowledge policies

System Interaction:

Self-service portal
Document module
Training system
3. Secondary Stakeholders
🔐 Security Team

Role: Ensures compliance and security enforcement

Responsibilities:

Monitor access violations
Audit system logs
Enforce security policies
Investigate anomalies

System Interaction:

Audit logs
Access control reports
💰 Finance Team

Role: Handles payroll and settlements

Responsibilities:

Activate payroll after onboarding
Process final settlement during offboarding
Validate employment status

System Interaction:

HR data sync
Offboarding module
⚙️ System Administrators

Role: Maintain system infrastructure

Responsibilities:

Configure workflows
Manage integrations
Monitor system health
Handle deployments
4. External Stakeholders
☁️ IAM Providers

Examples:

Microsoft (Azure Active Directory / Entra ID)
Okta Identity Platform
Google Workspace

Role:

Handle authentication and access provisioning
📄 Document/E-Sign Providers
Contract signing platforms
Compliance document systems
📊 HR Systems (Source of Truth)
Workday / BambooHR-type systems (if integrated)
5. Stakeholder Power vs Interest Matrix
High Power / High Interest
- HR Team
- IT Team
- Security Team

High Power / Low Interest
- Finance Team
- System Admins

Low Power / High Interest
- Employees
- Managers

Low Power / Low Interest
- External vendors (IAM tools)
6. Stakeholder Interaction Flow
Onboarding Flow
HR → Creates Employee
   ↓
Manager → Approves Request
   ↓
IT → Provisions Access
   ↓
IAM Provider → Creates Accounts
   ↓
Employee → Completes Tasks
   ↓
Security → Monitors Logs
Offboarding Flow
Manager → Initiates Exit
   ↓
HR → Approves Exit
   ↓
IT → Revokes Access
   ↓
Finance → Processes Settlement
   ↓
Security → Validates Logs
   ↓
System → Archives Employee
7. Stakeholder Needs Mapping
Stakeholder	Need	System Feature
HR	Fast onboarding	Automated workflows
IT	Secure provisioning	IAM integration
Managers	Visibility	Dashboard & approvals
Employees	Clarity	Self-service portal
Security	Compliance	Audit logs
Finance	Accuracy	HR data sync
8. Communication Channels
Email notifications
Workflow dashboards
Slack / Teams alerts
Audit reports
Approval requests
9. Conflict Handling Between Stakeholders
Conflict	Resolution Rule
HR vs IT delays	SLA-based escalation
Manager delays approvals	Auto-reminder system
Employee missing docs	Workflow pause
Security flag vs HR urgency	Security overrides HR
10. Stakeholder Dependency Chain
HR → Manager → IT → IAM → Employee → Security → Finance

Each step depends on the previous one being completed successfully.
